name: BufferGeometry
documentation:
This is a superefficent class for geometries because it saves all data in buffers.
It reduces memory costs and cpu cycles. But it is not as easy to work with because of all the nessecary buffer calculations.
It is mainly interesting when working with static objects.

name: Geometry

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique number of this geometry instance

properties.name: name
properties.documentation: Name for this geometry. Default is an empty string.

properties.name: vertices
properties.documentation:
The array of vertices hold every position of points of the model.
To signal an update in this array, Geometry.verticesNeedUpdate needs to be set to true.

properties.name: colors
properties.documentation:
Array of vertex colors, matching number and order of vertices.
Used in ParticleSystem, Line and Ribbon.
Meshes use per-face-use-of-vertex colors embedded directly in faces.
To signal an update in this array, Geometry.colorsNeedUpdate needs to be set to true.

properties.name: faces
properties.documentation:
Array of triangles or/and quads.
The array of faces describe how each vertex in the model is connected with each other.
To signal an update in this array, Geometry.elementsNeedUpdate needs to be set to true.

properties.name: faceVertexUvs
properties.documentation:
Array of face UV layers.
Each UV layer is an array of UV matching order and number of vertices in faces.
To signal an update in this array, Geometry.uvsNeedUpdate needs to be set to true.

properties.name: morphTargets
morphNormals

Array of morph normals. Morph normals have similar structure as morph targets, each normal set is a Javascript object:

     morphNormal = { name: "NormalName", normals: [ new THREE.Vector3(), ... ] }

properties.documentation: Set to true if the normals array has been updated.

name: Material
documentation: Materials describe the appearance of objects. They are defined in a (mostly) renderer-independent way, so you don't have to rewrite materials if you decide to use a different renderer.

properties.name: alphaTest
properties.documentation: Sets the alpha value to be used when running an alpha test. Default is 0.

properties.name: blendDst
properties.documentation: Blending destination. It's one of the blending mode constants defined in Three.js. Default is {@link OneMinusSrcAlphaFactor}.

properties.name: blendDstAlpha
properties.documentation: The tranparency of the .blendDst. Default is null.

properties.name: blendEquation
properties.documentation: Blending equation to use when applying blending. It's one of the constants defined in Three.js. Default is {@link AddEquation}.

properties.name: blendEquationAlpha
properties.documentation: The tranparency of the .blendEquation. Default is null.

properties.name: blending
properties.documentation: Which blending to use when displaying objects with this material. Default is {@link NormalBlending}.

properties.name: blendSrc
properties.documentation: Blending source. It's one of the blending mode constants defined in Three.js. Default is {@link SrcAlphaFactor}.

properties.name: blendSrcAlpha
properties.documentation: The tranparency of the .blendSrc. Default is null.

properties.name: clipIntersection
properties.documentation: Changes the behavior of clipping planes so that only their intersection is clipped, rather than their union. Default is false.

properties.name: clippingPlanes
properties.documentation: User-defined clipping planes specified as THREE.Plane objects in world space. These planes apply to the objects this material is attached to. Points in space whose signed distance to the plane is negative are clipped (not rendered). See the WebGL / clipping /intersection example. Default is null.

properties.name: clipShadows
properties.documentation: Defines whether to clip shadows according to the clipping planes specified on this material. Default is false.

properties.name: colorWrite
properties.documentation: Whether to render the material's color. This can be used in conjunction with a mesh's .renderOrder property to create invisible objects that occlude other objects. Default is true.

properties.name: depthFunc
properties.documentation: Which depth function to use. Default is {@link LessEqualDepth}. See the depth mode constants for all possible values.

properties.name: depthTest
properties.documentation: Whether to have depth test enabled when rendering this material. Default is true.

properties.name: depthWrite
properties.documentation:
Whether rendering this material has any effect on the depth buffer. Default is true.
When drawing 2D overlays it can be useful to disable the depth writing in order to layer several things together without creating z-index artifacts.

properties.name: fog
properties.documentation: Whether the material is affected by fog. Default is true.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique number of this material instance.

properties.name: isMaterial
properties.documentation:
Used to check whether this or derived classes are materials. Default is true.
You should not change this, as it used internally for optimisation.

properties.name: lights
properties.documentation: Whether the material is affected by lights. Default is true.

properties.name: name
properties.documentation: Material name. Default is an empty string.

properties.name: needsUpdate
properties.documentation:
Specifies that the material needs to be updated, WebGL wise. Set it to true if you made changes that need to be reflected in WebGL.
This property is automatically set to true when instancing a new material.

properties.name: opacity
properties.documentation: Opacity. Default is 1.

properties.name: overdraw
properties.documentation: Enables/disables overdraw. If greater than zero, polygons are drawn slightly bigger in order to fix antialiasing gaps when using the CanvasRenderer. Default is 0.

properties.name: polygonOffset
properties.documentation: Whether to use polygon offset. Default is false. This corresponds to the POLYGON_OFFSET_FILL WebGL feature.

properties.name: polygonOffsetFactor
properties.documentation: Sets the polygon offset factor. Default is 0.

properties.name: polygonOffsetUnits
properties.documentation: Sets the polygon offset units. Default is 0.

properties.name: precision
properties.documentation: Override the renderer's default precision for this material. Can be "highp", "mediump" or "lowp". Defaults is null.

properties.name: premultipliedAlpha
properties.documentation: Whether to premultiply the alpha (transparency) value. See WebGL / Materials / Transparency for an example of the difference. Default is false.

properties.name: dithering
properties.documentation: Whether to apply dithering to the color to remove the appearance of banding. Default is false.

properties.name: flatShading
properties.documentation: Define whether the material is rendered with flat shading. Default is false.

properties.name: side
properties.documentation:
Defines which of the face sides will be rendered - front, back or both.
Default is THREE.FrontSide. Other options are THREE.BackSide and THREE.DoubleSide.

properties.name: transparent
properties.documentation:
Defines whether this material is transparent. This has an effect on rendering as transparent objects need special treatment and are rendered after non-transparent objects.
When set to true, the extent to which the material is transparent is controlled by setting it's .opacity property.
Default is false.

properties.name: type
properties.documentation: Value is the string 'Material'. This shouldn't be changed, and can be used to find all objects of this type in a scene.

properties.name: uuid
properties.documentation: UUID of this material instance. This gets automatically assigned, so this shouldn't be edited.

properties.name: vertexColors
properties.documentation: Defines whether vertex coloring is used. Default is THREE.NoColors. Other options are THREE.VertexColors and THREE.FaceColors.

properties.name: visible
properties.documentation: Defines whether this material is visible. Default is true.

properties.name: userData
properties.documentation: An object that can be used to store custom data about the Material. It should not hold references to functions as these will not be cloned.

methods.name: clone
methods.documentation: Return a new material with the same parameters as this material.

methods.name: copy
methods.documentation: Copy the parameters from the passed material into this material.

methods.name: dispose
methods.documentation: This disposes the material. Textures of a material don't get disposed. These needs to be disposed by {@link Texture}.

methods.name: setValues
methods.documentation: Sets the properties based on the values.

methods.name: toJSON

name: Fog
documentation: This class contains the parameters that define linear fog, i.e., that grows linearly denser with the distance.

properties.documentation: The minimum distance to start applying fog. Objects that are less than 'near' units from the active camera won't be affected by fog.

properties.name: far
properties.documentation:
The maximum distance at which fog stops being calculated and applied. Objects that are more than 'far' units away from the active camera won't be affected by fog.
Default is 1000.

parameters.name: thetaStart
parameters.documentation: specify vertical starting angle. Default is 0.

parameters.name: thetaLength
parameters.documentation: specify vertical sweep angle size. Default is Math.PI.

constructors.documentation: The geometry is created by sweeping and calculating vertexes around the Y axis (horizontal sweep) and the Z axis (vertical sweep). Thus, incomplete spheres (akin to 'sphere slices') can be created through the use of different values of phiStart, phiLength, thetaStart and thetaLength, in order to define the points in which we start (or end) calculating those vertices.

properties.name: stageParameters
properties.documentation:
If this VRDisplay supports room-scale experiences, the optional
stage attribute contains details on the room-scale parameters.

properties.name: displayId
properties.documentation:
An identifier for this distinct VRDisplay. Used as an
association point in the Gamepad API.

properties.name: displayName
properties.documentation: A display name, a user-readable name identifying it.

properties.name: depthNear
properties.documentation:
z-depth defining the near plane of the eye view frustum
enables mapping of values in the render target depth
attachment to scene coordinates. Initially set to 0.01.

properties.name: depthFar
properties.documentation:
z-depth defining the far plane of the eye view frustum
enables mapping of values in the render target depth
attachment to scene coordinates. Initially set to 10000.0.

methods.name: getFrameData
methods.documentation:
Populates the passed VRFrameData with the information required to render
the current frame.

methods.name: getPose
methods.documentation:
Return a VRPose containing the future predicted pose of the VRDisplay
when the current frame will be presented. The value returned will not
change until JavaScript has returned control to the browser.

The VRPose will contain the position, orientation, velocity,
and acceleration of each of these properties.

methods.name: getImmediatePose
methods.documentation:
Return the current instantaneous pose of the VRDisplay, with no
prediction applied.

methods.name: resetPose
methods.documentation:
Reset the pose for this display, treating its current position and
orientation as the "origin/zero" values. VRPose.position,
VRPose.orientation, and VRStageParameters.sittingToStandingTransform may be
updated when calling resetPose(). This should be called in only
sitting-space experiences.

methods.name: requestAnimationFrame
methods.documentation:
The callback passed to `requestAnimationFrame` will be called
any time a new frame should be rendered. When the VRDisplay is
presenting the callback will be called at the native refresh
rate of the HMD. When not presenting this function acts
identically to how window.requestAnimationFrame acts. Content should
make no assumptions of frame rate or vsync behavior as the HMD runs
asynchronously from other displays and at differing refresh rates.

methods.name: cancelAnimationFrame
methods.documentation:
Passing the value returned by `requestAnimationFrame` to
`cancelAnimationFrame` will unregister the callback.

methods.name: requestPresent
methods.documentation:
Begin presenting to the VRDisplay. Must be called in response to a user gesture.
Repeat calls while already presenting will update the VRLayers being displayed.

methods.name: exitPresent
methods.documentation: Stops presenting to the VRDisplay.

methods.name: getLayers
methods.documentation: Get the layers currently being presented.

methods.name: submitFrame
methods.documentation:
The VRLayer provided to the VRDisplay will be captured and presented
in the HMD. Calling this function has the same effect on the source
canvas as any other operation that uses its source image, and canvases
created without preserveDrawingBuffer set to true will be cleared.
